{"Body": "<strong>R\u00f3n\u00e1n Burtenshaw</strong>\n<em>Staff Writer</em>\n<em></em>The College Finance Committee has approved a four per cent increase in rent on College accomodation.\n\nIn its meeting the Committee noted &lsquo;the cost base associated with residential activity had been re-examined after further consideration had been given to the current economic climate and other external factors.&rsquo;\n\nGraham Daniels, the Director of Accommodation and Catering told the Committee that &lsquo;whilst some small savings were made under some budget headings in the course of the review, there was no material change to the cost estimates presented.&rsquo;\n\nThe Committee had a short discussion on the item and decided to accept the four per cent increase in order &lsquo;to achieve a break even position in 2009/10.&rsquo;\n\nThe Students&rsquo; Union President, C\u00f3n\u00e1n \u00d3 Broin\u00a0 noted his disappointment with the\u00a0 increase, saying that &lsquo;rent in Dublin, as a whole, has been falling since the start of the recession it seems odd to be putting rent in College up.&rsquo;\n\nThe Daft.ie rent survey found that rent in Dublin has fallen by secenteen per cent over the last twelve months. Which has meant cheaper accomadation for students this year when compared with last year.\n\nThe College states a number of reasons for the increase in rent the first being that the College did not increase its rent in line with the increases in the private rental market over the last few years.\n\nThe College would also like to draw attention to the fact that there are increased amenities and costs assosisted with running rooms on the campus.\n\nThe number of beds on campus has been reduced a little this year due to the construction work being unertaken on the rooms in New Square. It is expected to increase again when these rooms are completed.", "Imageurl": "<strong>R\u00f3n\u00e1n Burtenshaw</strong>\n<em>Staff Writer</em>\n<em></em>The College Finance Committee has approved a four per cent increase in rent on College accomodation.\n\nIn its meeting the Committee noted &lsquo;the cost base associated with residential activity had been re-examined after further consideration had been given to the current economic climate and other external factors.&rsquo;\n\nGraham Daniels, the Director of Accommodation and Catering told the Committee that &lsquo;whilst some small savings were made under some budget headings in the course of the review, there was no material change to the cost estimates presented.&rsquo;\n\nThe Committee had a short discussion on the item and decided to accept the four per cent increase in order &lsquo;to achieve a break even position in 2009/10.&rsquo;\n\nThe Students&rsquo; Union President, C\u00f3n\u00e1n \u00d3 Broin\u00a0 noted his disappointment with the\u00a0 increase, saying that &lsquo;rent in Dublin, as a whole, has been falling since the start of the recession it seems odd to be putting rent in College up.&rsquo;\n\nThe Daft.ie rent survey found that rent in Dublin has fallen by secenteen per cent over the last twelve months. Which has meant cheaper accomadation for students this year when compared with last year.\n\nThe College states a number of reasons for the increase in rent the first being that the College did not increase its rent in line with the increases in the private rental market over the last few years.\n\nThe College would also like to draw attention to the fact that there are increased amenities and costs assosisted with running rooms on the campus.\n\nThe number of beds on campus has been reduced a little this year due to the construction work being unertaken on the rooms in New Square. It is expected to increase again when these rooms are completed.", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "366", "Heading": "College rooms up by four  per cent"}